Q1a) Network of Followers

Modifications in node files (ofc manully): remove node “SenBennetCO”, cuz its not in the edges. Three most popular senators is shown below. Brief comment: it seems to me that democratic senators have smaller networks than the republicans. Also, we can see two clear clusters of each party.

q1 <- read.csv("C:/Users/pb061/Documents/GitHub/course_materials/Exercises/10_twittersenate/senators_follow.csv")
q12 <- read.csv("C:/Users/pb061/Documents/GitHub/course_materials/Exercises/10_twittersenate/senators_twitter.csv")
# clean it....
q1a <- q1[which(q1['following']==TRUE),]
edges <- data.frame(source = q1a$source,target = q1a$target)
# head(edges)
nodes <- data.frame(node = q12$Official.Twitter, party = q12$Party.affiliation)
nodes <- nodes[which(nodes$node !='SenBennetCO'),]
nodes$node <- tolower(nodes$node)
edges$source <- tolower(edges$source)
edges$target <- tolower(edges$target)

net <- graph_from_data_frame(edges,vertices = nodes)
indegree = igraph::degree(net,mode = 'in')
outdegree = igraph::degree(net,mode = 'out')
sort(indegree,decreasing = TRUE)[1:3]
##  senjohnkennedy senatorcantwell sensherrodbrown 
##              95              95              94
sort(outdegree,decreasing = TRUE)[1:3]
##      senshelby senatorcollins  lisamurkowski 
##            119             85             78
V(net)$Popularity <- degree(net, mode = 'in')

# plot using ggraph
ggraph(net, layout = 'kk') + 
    geom_edge_fan(show.legend = FALSE)+
  scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "gray", "red"))+
    geom_node_point(aes(size = Popularity,colour = party))

# cleaning the data
removeCapt <- function(x){gsub("^[A-Z]+ ", "", x)}
removeNumPunct <- function(x){gsub("[^[:alpha:][:space:]]*", "", x)}
clean_corpus <- function(corpus){
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removePunctuation)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus,  content_transformer(removeCapt) )
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(tolower))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeWords, c(stopwords("en")))  
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, removeNumbers)
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, content_transformer(removeNumPunct))
  corpus <- tm_map(corpus, stripWhitespace)
  return(corpus)
}

# visualize the worldcloud.....
tmp1 <- data.frame(doc_id = subset$status_id,text = subset$text,who =subset$screen_name,party=subset$Party.affiliation)
s1 = paste(tmp1$text[tmp1$party=="Democratic Party"],collapse = " ")
s2 = paste(tmp1$text[tmp1$party=="Republican Party"],collapse = " ")
s3 <- data.frame(doc_id = c("Democratic Party","Republican Party"), text= c(s1,s2),stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
s3 <- VCorpus(DataframeSource(s3) )

s3_cl <- clean_corpus(s3)

mx <- as.matrix( TermDocumentMatrix(s3_cl) )
comparison.cloud(mx, colors = c( "blue","red"), 
                 scale=c(0.1,2), title.size= 3, 
                 max.words = 1000)

Q3 Are you talking to me?

Q3a) Identifying Re-Tweets

The results show that generally, senators only retweet tweets from their from their own party. <> “markwarner”,“chrismurphyct”,“senatorisakson” and “senschumer” get a lot of retweets than other people.And yes, senators do re-tweet their own party colleagues’ messages.

nodes <- data.frame(node = q12$Official.Twitter, party = q12$Party.affiliation)
nodes$node <- tolower(nodes$node)

q3 <- senator_tweets[which(senator_tweets$is_retweet==TRUE),]
q3$retweet_screen_name <- tolower(q3$retweet_screen_name)
names(nodes)[2] <- 'retweet_party'
q3a <- merge(q3,nodes,by.x= 'retweet_screen_name',by.y = 'node')
names(nodes)[2] <- 'party'

q3a <- merge(q3a,nodes,by.x= 'screen_name',by.y = 'node')
tmp<-data.frame(a = q3a$retweet_screen_name,b = q3a$retweet_party,c = q3a$screen_name,party = q3a$party)
res<- aggregate(cbind(count = a )~ a+ party,data = tmp,FUN = function(x){NROW(x)}) 
res2 <- res[order(res$a),][1:30,]
tmp <- merge(res,nodes,by.x = 'a',by.y = 'node')
ggplot(data=res2, aes(x=a, y=count, fill = party) )+  geom_bar(stat = "identity")+ scale_fill_manual(values = c('red','gray','blue') )+ xlab("who?") + ylab("counts") + coord_flip() + ggtitle("Identifying Re-Tweets")

Q3b Identifying Mentions

q3 <- senator_tweets[which(senator_tweets$is_retweet!=FALSE),]

q3b <- data.frame(from = NA,to = NA)
for (i in 1:length(q3$user_id) ) {
  lvar = tolower(q3$mentions_screen_name[[i]])
  for (j in 1:length(nodes$node)){
    if (nodes$node[j] %in% lvar){
      q3b <-rbind(q3b,c(nodes$node[j],tolower(q3$screen_name[i])))
    }
  }
}

q3b2 <- q3b[which(q3b$from!=q3b$to),]
q3b23 <- aggregate(cbind(wei = from )~ from + to,data =q3b2,FUN = function(x){NROW(x)}) 

net2 <- graph_from_data_frame(q3b23,directed = FALSE,vertices = nodes)
V(net2)$Popularity <- degree(net2)

# plot using ggraph
ggraph(net2, layout = 'kk', maxiter = 100) + 
    geom_edge_fan(aes(edge_width= wei),show.legend = FALSE)+scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "gray", "red"))+
    geom_node_point(aes(size = Popularity,colour = party))+ggtitle("Identifying Mentions")
